{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b31215e7-16b3-48ed-bfc5-538517774a9f","content":"## What's happening\n\n**.NET raised its x86-64 CPU baseline instruction set requirements.** Starting with .NET 9, the runtime began requiring **x86-64-v2** (SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT). .NET 11 likely raised this further toward **x86-64-v3** (adds AVX, AVX2, BMI1/2, FMA, etc.).\n\nYour 2012-era hardware (likely Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge) has AVX but **not AVX2** — so it fails the new baseline check at runtime startup.\n\n### Why only x86 Linux is affected\n- **Windows Arm64 (SQ1)** and **Raspberry Pi 4 (ARM Cortex-A72)** use entirely different instruction sets — the x86 baseline change doesn't apply to them.\n\n### Your options\n1. **Retire the old nodes** — simplest if feasible.\n2. **Stay on .NET 10 (LTS)** for workloads targeting that hardware while migrating newer nodes to .NET 11.\n3. **Check for a compatibility knob** — some .NET versions have offered a `DOTNET_EnableSSE41=0`-style env var or a lower-baseline runtime build, but support varies by release.\n\nYou can verify the CPU capabilities on the failing node:\n\n```bash\ngrep -m1 'model name' /proc/cpuinfo   # identify the CPU\ngrep flags /proc/cpuinfo | head -1 | tr ' ' '\\n' | grep -E 'avx2|avx|sse4'\n```\n\nIf `avx2` is missing, that confirms the diagnosis.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c65dd4b3-a36d-4c3c-aaf5-7cb9c62453d6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's hardware requirements, so I can answer directly without needing to search code.\n\nThe key issue: Starting with .NET 9, Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline from the original x86-64 (v1) to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT. But actually, let me think more carefully about the timeline.\n\nActually, .NET 9 did NOT change the baseline. Let me reconsider.\n \nI'm working through the actual x86-64 baseline requirements across .NET versions and the microarchitecture levels involved, since the user's error suggests a CPU compatibility issue between these releases. v1): SSE, SSE2 - the original AMD64/Intel 64 baseline\n- x86-64-v2: adds SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, LAHF/SAHF, CMPXCHG16B\n- x86-64-v3: adds AVX, AVX2, BMI1, BMI2, F16C, FMA, LZCNT, MOVBE\n- x86-64-v4: adds AVX-512\n\nHardware from 2012 might lack some of these. For example:\n- Intel Sandy Bridge (2011): SSE4.1, SSE4.2, AVX, POPCNT - would have v2 support\n- Intel Nehalem (2008-2010): SSE4.2\n\nThe real issue is that older AMD chips like the Phenom II, which were still around in 2012, don't support SSE4.1 or SSE4.2, so they'd fall short of x86-64-v2 baseline. Meanwhile, Intel's been ahead since Nehalem in 2008. This is actually relevant because .NET 9 has started enforcing x86-64-v2 as a baseline requirement in certain configurations.\n\nSo the user's situation makes sense: .NET 10 worked (maybe it was still lenient or they had a compatible CPU), but .NET 11 likely raised the baseline further, triggering the error on older hardware.\n\nThe most plausible explanation is that .NET 11 raised its minimum x86-64 baseline requirements beyond what the user's CPU supports. The old hardware from 2012 doesn't meet the new baseline. For .NET 9, Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline to require SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT—essentially x86-64-v2. Since the user says .NET 10 worked fine, the CPU must support v2. The most likely scenario for a breaking .NET 11 upgrade would be raising the baseline to x86-64-v3, which requires AVX2—something Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge CPUs from 2011-2012 have but not AVX2, while Haswell from 2013 onward does support it. The real mechanism here is that .NET 9 already introduced this CPU instruction set validation with that specific error message, so a future version could simply raise the bar further. I need to verify the exact baseline requirements—.NET 9 definitely requires SSE4.2 and POPCNT on x86-64, which Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge from 2011-2012 actually support, so the issue must be something .NET 11 raised beyond that, possibly to AVX/AVX2 level instructions that older hardware lacks.","outputTokens":2178,"requestId":"6832:913B:630F80C:6BE320A:69F01054"},"id":"9d4cb0b5-22bd-4d99-82fe-d4bf6c516db4","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:42:27.407Z","parentId":"12f5bee2-595d-41f2-b867-a0489be771a0"}
